          "body": "Verse 16 is brief but theologically significant: 'Fathers shall not be put to death for their sons, nor shall sons be put to death for their fathers; everyone shall be put to death for his own sin.' In the ancient Near East, collective family punishment was standard judicial practice — a rebel's household could be executed alongside him. Moses prohibits this. Guilt is not hereditary; accountability is individual. This principle is echoed and expanded by Ezekiel (18:1-32) against the proverb 'The fathers eat sour grapes and the children's teeth are set on edge.' 2 Kings 14:6 explicitly cites Deuteronomy 24:16 when Amaziah spares the sons of his father's assassins. The New Testament carries the same principle forward: each person stands before God on the basis of his own response to Christ (Romans 14:12; 2 Corinthians 5:10). The verse is not a denial of the solidarity of the human race in Adam (Romans 5:12-21) — that is a different category — but a protection against judicial systems that punish the innocent for another's guilt."
