        "title": "Divorce regulated, not endorsed — protecting the woman from disposability",
        "range": "24:1-4",
        "excerpt": "He writes her a certificate of divorce and puts it in her hand and sends her out from his house… then her former husband who sent her away is not allowed to take her again to be his wife, since she has been defiled; for that is an abomination before the Lord.",
        "body": "The most important interpretive move in reading 24:1-4 is to identify what Moses is actually legislating. The passage is a single conditional sentence: four 'if' clauses (24:1-3) lead to one 'then' clause (24:4). The actual law — the apodosis — is the prohibition in verse 4. Moses is not instituting divorce; he is prohibiting one specific remarriage scenario. The certificate requirement (*sepher keritut*, 'document of cutting') is assumed as existing practice; Moses requires its formalization to protect the woman. Without a written document, a dismissed wife had no legal standing to remarry; the certificate was her freedom paper.\n\nThe ground for the prohibition in verse 4 is the word *tame* — 'she has been defiled.' This is the chapter's most debated interpretive crux. Most evangelical commentators (Peter Craigie, *The Book of Deuteronomy*, NICOT; Chris Wright, *Deuteronomy*, NIBC) read the defilement as the result of the second marriage, not as moral condemnation of the woman — she is not guilty, but a sexual and covenantal bond has been established that cannot simply be reversed by the first husband's renewed interest. The woman is not a commodity to be returned when the second arrangement fails. The Levitical purity logic (cf. Leviticus 18) operates here: certain unions, once contracted, alter the relational landscape in ways that cannot be undone.\n\nJesus enters this legal debate directly in Matthew 19:3-9. When Pharisees ask whether divorce is permitted 'for any cause,' Jesus distinguishes the Mosaic permission from the Mosaic (and divine) intention. 'Moses permitted you to divorce your wives because of your hardness of heart, but from the beginning it was not this way' (Matthew 19:8). The 'beginning' is Genesis 2:24 — one flesh, permanent bond. Deuteronomy 24 is thus a concession to human sinfulness, not a transcript of the marriage ideal. The certificate requirement protects women within a system that Moses knew he could not simply abolish; the remarriage prohibition protects women from becoming pawns in a man's revolving domestic arrangements.\n\nThe land-defilement clause ('you shall not bring sin on the land,' 24:4) connects the domestic regulation to the covenant theology of the land. The land is Yahweh's inheritance given to Israel (24:4); moral abominations defile it (Leviticus 18:25-28). The chapter opens, therefore, with the most intimate human institution (marriage) and immediately frames it in terms of the land's holiness — a reminder that private conduct and national covenant health are never separable in Deuteronomy's world.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ervah davar* (some indecency, 24:1) — literally 'nakedness of a thing,' an ambiguous phrase that generated the famous Shammai/Hillel debate in first-century Judaism (Shammai: adultery only; Hillel: any displeasure). Jesus does not adjudicate the Hillel/Shammai debate; He moves behind it to Genesis. *Toevah* (abomination, 24:4) — the same term used in Leviticus 18:22, 26-30 for sexually defiling practices; its appearance here signals that the remarriage prohibition is cultic-covenantal, not merely civil."
