        "title": "The person behind the pledge — dignity over collateral",
        "range": "24:5-13",
        "excerpt": "No one shall take a handmill or an upper millstone in pledge, for he would be taking a life in pledge… If he is a poor man, you shall not sleep with his pledge. When the sun goes down you shall surely return the pledge to him.",
        "body": "Verses 5-13 group three laws that, on the surface, appear unrelated: the military exemption for new husbands (24:5), the prohibition on millstone pledges (24:6), and the kidnapping statute (24:7), before arriving at the detailed pledge-return law (24:10-13). The editorial logic is a meditation on what it means to respect a person rather than exploit their circumstance. The newly married man's year of freedom (24:5) is the first form of this principle: the state may not conscript a man away from the covenant he has just entered. The military machine must yield to the marriage covenant.\n\nThe millstone prohibition (24:6) deploys the pivotal word *nephesh* — life, self, the whole person. To take a millstone as pledge is to take a *nephesh* as pledge. Bread was ground daily in Israelite households; a millstone was not a luxury asset but a survival tool. The law distinguishes between legitimate collateral (assets that can be surrendered temporarily without destroying livelihood) and illegitimate collateral (assets whose surrender is functionally an assault on the debtor's ability to live). The principle has wide application: no creditor may demand, as security, the thing that makes a person capable of sustaining life.\n\nThe pledge-return law (24:10-13) extends this logic with two further specifications. First, the creditor must remain outside the debtor's house (24:10-11) — the debtor selects and brings out his own pledge. The creditor's power to demand collateral does not translate into a right to enter and search the debtor's domestic space. The threshold marks the boundary of personal dignity. Second, a poor man's cloak must be returned at sunset (24:12-13). In ancient Palestine, a cloak (*salmah*) served as a blanket at night; keeping it was keeping the man cold. The deadline is not sunset-approximately but sunset-exactly: 'when the sun goes down you shall surely return' — the doubled verb in Hebrew (*hashev tashiv*) is emphatic.\n\nThe covenantal reward for cloak-return is striking: 'it will be righteousness for you before the Lord your God' (24:13). Douglas Moo's comment on the parallel New Testament theme applies here: practical mercy is not a supplement to covenant righteousness but its enacted form. The act of returning a cloak at nightfall is *tsedaqah* — the same term used for Abraham's faith counted as righteousness (Genesis 15:6). The chapter refuses to separate social ethics from covenant standing.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nephesh* (life/soul, 24:6, 7) — the whole person, not merely the rational soul of Greek anthropology; to seize a man's *nephesh* is to seize him. *Salmah* (cloak, 24:13) — the outer garment that served as blanket; Exodus 22:26-27 gives the same law with the motive 'it is his only covering; it is his cloak for his body — in what shall he sleep? And when he cries to Me, I will hear him, for I am gracious.' Deuteronomy 24 is stricter: the return is required regardless of whether the man cries out."
